  <page>
    <title>Communications in Afghanistan</title>
    <id>6684</id>
    <revision>
      <id>425359037</id>
      <timestamp>2011-04-22T16:29:21Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <username>Hkrclu</username>
        <id>10916523</id>
      </contributor>
      <minor />
      <comment>/* Internet */</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">'''Communications in [[Afghanistan]]''' has dramatically increased since 2002, and has embarked on wireless companies, internet, radio stations and television channels. Afghan telecommunication companies, such as [[Afghan Wireless]] and [[Roshan (Telecom)|Roshan]], have been boasting rapid increase in cellular phone usage in the mid 2000s. In response to this [[Etisalat]] and [[MTN Group]] were launched in 2007. 

The [[Ministry of Communications (Afghanistan)|Afghan Ministry of Communications]] signed a $64.5 agreement in 2006 with China's [[ZTE]] on the establishment of a countrywide [[optical fiber]] [[cable network]]. The plan was intended to improve telephone, internet, television and radio broadcast services throughout the country.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.pajhwok.com/viewstory.asp?lng=eng&amp;id=26882 ''Ministry signs contract with Chinese company''], Pajhwok Afghan News.&lt;/ref&gt;

==Telephone==
{{See|Telephone numbers in Afghanistan}}
There are 12 million [[mobile phone]] lines (cellular phone lines) in Afghanistan as of 2009&lt;ref&gt;[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2151.html?countryName=Afghanistan&amp;countryCode=af&amp;regionCode=sas&amp;#af CIA - The World Factbook - Field Listing :: Telephones - mobile cellular&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt;, but only 129,300 [[landline|fixed-telephone-lines]]. Mobile communications have improved because of the introduction of wireless carriers into this [[developing country]]. The first was [[Afghan Wireless]], which is US based that was founded by [[Ehsan Bayat]]. The second was [[Roshan (telco)|Roshan]], which began providing services to all major cities within Afghanistan. There are also five or more [[VSAT]]'s installed in [[Kabul]], [[Kandahar]], [[Herat]], [[Mazari Sharif]], and [[Jalalabad]], providing international and domestic voice/data connectivity. The international calling code for Afghanistan is [[Telephone numbers in Afghanistan|+93]]. The following is a partial list of mobile phone companies in the country:

*[[Afghan Wireless]]
*[[Roshan (telco)|Roshan]]
*[[Etisalat]]
*[[MTN Group]] &lt;ref&gt;[http://www.areeba.com.af/Index.aspx Areeba Afghanistan&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.mtn.com MTN Group | Home&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt;

==Internet==
{{Main|Internet in Afghanistan}}
[[File:Afghan man reading Wikipedia article in Kandahar.jpg|thumb|Internet user at [[Kandahar University]]]]
Afghanistan was given legal control of the &quot;[[.af]]&quot; domain in 2003, and the Afghanistan Network Information Center (AFGNIC) was established to administer [[domain name]]s. As of 2020, there are at least 46 [[internet service provider]]s (ISPs) in the country.&lt;ref&gt;[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2184.html?countryName=Afghanistan&amp;countryCode=af&amp;regionCode=sas&amp;#af CIA - The World Factbook - Field Listing :: Internet hosts&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt; [[Internet in Afghanistan]] is also at the peak with 1 million users in 2009.&lt;ref&gt;[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2153.html?countryName=Afghanistan&amp;countryCode=af&amp;regionCode=sas&amp;#af CIA - The World Factbook - Field Listing :: Internet users&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt; The following is a partial list of the internet service providers operating in Afghanistan:

*[[Danesh Net]]
*[[Ts 2]] &lt;ref name=&quot;reuters.com&quot;&gt;{{cite news |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS152237+22-Jan-2009+PRN20090122 |work=Reuters |title=Satellite Broadband Internet in Iraq and Afghanistan for U.S. Troops |date=January 22, 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Television==
{{Main|List of television channels in Afghanistan}}
There are at least 8 [[television network]]s based inside Afghanistan, and about a dozen international broadcasters are available.

==Radio==
As of 2007, there are an estimated 50 private radio stations throughout the country. At least 5 are [[FM]], 21 [[amplitude modulation|AM]], and 1 [[shortwave]] (broadcasting in [[Pashto language|Pashto]], [[Dari (Afghanistan)|Dari]], and [[English language|English]] languages). The following is an incomplete list of radio channels broadcasing from within Afghanistan:

*[[Kabul Radio]]

==Postal service==
{{See also|Postage stamps and postal history of Afghanistan}}

In 1870, a central [[post office]] was established at [[Bala Hissar]] in Kabul and a post office in the capital of each province. The service was slowly being expanded over the years as more postal offices were established in each large city by 1918. Afghanistan became member of the [[Universal Postal Union]] in 1928, and the postal administration elevated to the [[Afghan Ministry of Communications|Ministry of Communication]] in 1934.&lt;ref&gt;{{citeweb|url=http://afghanpost.gov.af/about.htm|title=afghanpost.gov.af - About}}&lt;/ref&gt; Civil war caused a disruption in issuing official stamps during the 1980s-90s war&lt;ref name=fabio&gt;{{citeweb|url=http://digilander.libero.it/fabioalarici/a.html|title=Postal Authorities A}}&lt;/ref&gt; but in 1999 postal service was operating again. Postal services to/from Kabul worked remarkably well all throughout the war years. Postal services to/from Herat resumed in 1997. &lt;ref&gt;{{citeweb|url=http://www.afghan-network.net/Culture/stamps.html|title=Afghanistan @ Stamps}}&lt;/ref&gt; The Afghan government has reported to the UPU several times about illegal stamps being issued and sold in 2003 and 2007.&lt;ref&gt;{{citeweb|url=http://www.upu.int/philately/en/2003/002_upu_circular_en.pdf|title=2003 UPU Circular}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{citeweb|url=http://www.upu.int/philately/en/2007/177_upu_circular_en.pdf|title=2007 UPU Circular}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Afghanistan Post has been reorganizing the postal service in 2000s with the help of [[Pakistan Post]].&lt;ref name=fabio/&gt; The Afghanistan Postal commission was formed to prepare a written policy for the development of the postal sector, which will form the basis of a new postal services law governing licensing of postal services providers. The project was expected to finish by 2008.&lt;ref&gt;{{citeweb|url=http://www.mcit.gov.af/Documents/RunningProjects/AfghanPost.pdf|title=Afghanistan Postal commission}}&lt;/ref&gt;

