      <text xml:space="preserve">{{About|the beverage|its manufacturer|The Coca-Cola Company}}
{{Redirect|Coca-Cola Classic|the NCAA football game|Coca-Cola Classic (college football)}}
{{pp-semi-vandalism|small=yes}}{{pp-move-indef}}
{{infobox beverage
|name = Coca-Cola
|image = [[Image:Coca-Cola logo.svg|300px]]
|caption = 
|type = [[Soft drink]]
|manufacturer = [[The Coca-Cola Company]]
|origin = United States
|introduced = 1886
|color = Caramel E-150d
|flavor = Cola, Cola Cherry, Cola Vanilla, Cola Green Tea, Cola Lemon, Cola Lemon Lime, Cola Lime, Cola Orange and Cola Raspberry.
|variants = See [[#Brand portfolio|Brand portfolio]] section below
|related = [[Pepsi]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Irn Bru]]&lt;br /&gt; [[RC Cola]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Cola Turka]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Zam Zam Cola]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Mecca-Cola]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Virgin Cola]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Parsi Cola]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Qibla Cola]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Evoca Cola]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Corsica Cola]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Breizh Cola]]&lt;br /&gt;[[Afri Cola]]
|website =
}}
[[Image:World-of-coca-cola.jpg|thumb|The [[Las Vegas Strip]] ''[[World of Coca-Cola]]'' museum in 2003]]

'''Coca-Cola''' is a [[carbonation|carbonated]] [[soft drink]] sold in the stores, restaurants, and [[vending machine]]s of more than 200 countries.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | publisher=Coca-Cola official website | url=http://www.virtualvender.coca-cola.com/ft/index.jsp | title=Brand Fact Sheet | date=2008-12-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; It is produced by [[The Coca-Cola Company]] of [[Atlanta, Georgia]], and is often referred to simply as '''Coke''' (a registered trademark of The Coca-Cola Company in the United States since March 27, 1944). Originally intended as a [[patent medicine]] when it was invented in the late 19th century by [[John Pemberton]], Coca-Cola was bought out by businessman [[Asa Griggs Candler]], whose marketing tactics led Coke to its dominance of the world soft-drink market throughout the 20th century.

The company produces [[concentrate]], which is then sold to licensed Coca-Cola bottlers throughout the world. The bottlers, who hold territorially exclusive contracts with the company, produce finished product in cans and bottles from the concentrate in combination with filtered water and sweeteners. The bottlers then sell, distribute and merchandise Coca-Cola to retail stores and vending machines. Such bottlers include [[Coca-Cola Enterprises]], which is the largest single Coca-Cola bottler in North America and western Europe. The Coca-Cola Company also sells concentrate for [[soda fountain]]s to major restaurants and [[food service]] distributors.

The Coca-Cola Company has, on occasion, introduced other cola drinks under the Coke brand name. The most common of these is [[Diet Coke]], with others including [[Caffeine-Free Coca-Cola]], Diet Coke Caffeine-Free, [[Coca-Cola Cherry]], [[Coca-Cola Zero]], [[Coca-Cola Vanilla]], and special editions with lemon, lime or coffee.

In response to consumer insistence on a more natural product, the company is in the process of phasing out E211, or [[sodium benzoate]], the controversial additive used in Diet Coke and linked to [[DNA]] damage in yeast cells and hyperactivity in children. The company has stated that it plans to remove E211 from its other products, including [[Sprite (soft drink)|Sprite]] and [[Oasis (drink)|Oasis]], as soon as a satisfactory alternative is found.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news | publisher=The Daily Mail | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1021820/Diet-Coke-drop-additive-DNA-damage-fear.html | title=DNA Damage Fear | date=2008-05-24 | location=London | first=Colin | last=Fernandez}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==History==
[[Image:- Coca-Cola - Old bottle opener -.jpg|left|thumb|Old German Coca-Cola [[bottle opener]]]]
[[File:19th century Coca-Cola coupon.jpg|thumb|250px|Believed to be the first coupon ever, this ticket for a free glass of Coca-Cola was first distributed in 1888 to help promote the drink. By 1913, the company had redeemed 8.5 million tickets.&lt;ref&gt;{{citation |title=First Coupon Ever |last=Geuss |first=Megan |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |volume=18 |number=11 |date=October 2010 |page=104}}&lt;/ref&gt;]]
[[Image:Coca Cola ad ca. 1943 IMG 3744.JPG|thumb|This Coca-Cola advertisement from 1943 is still displayed in the small city of [[Minden, Louisiana|Minden]], [[Louisiana]].]]
The [[prototype]] Coca-Cola recipe was formulated at the Eagle Drug and Chemical Company, a drugstore in [[Columbus, Georgia|Columbus]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] by [[John Pemberton]], originally as a [[coca wine]] called [[Pemberton's French Wine Coca]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://files.usgwarchives.net/ga/muscogee/photos/pemberto13411gph.txt |title=Coca Cola Inventor was Local Pharmacist, Columbus Ledger |date= |accessdate=2011-03-13}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.gadailynews.com/news/columbus/64433-columbus-helped-make-coke-x2019-s-success-x2018-the-real-thing-x2019.html |title=Columbus helped make Coke’s success}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.coca-cola.co.uk/ourbrands/default.aspx?id=9 |title=Coca-Cola&amp;nbsp; — Our Brands |accessdate=2007-02-11 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt; He may have been inspired by the formidable success of [[Vin Mariani]], a European coca wine.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Mark Pendergrast | title=For God, Country and Coca-Cola | publisher=Basic Books | year=2000 | page=25 | isbn=0-465-05468-4 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 1886, when Atlanta and [[Fulton County, Georgia|Fulton County]] passed [[prohibition]] legislation, Pemberton responded by developing Coca-Cola, essentially a non-alcoholic version of French Wine Coca.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |first=Jack |last=Hayes |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Coca-Cola Television Advertisements: Dr. John S. Pemberton |url=http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/ccmphtml/colainvnt.html |work= |publisher=Nation's Restaurant News |date= |accessdate=2007-01-21 }}&lt;/ref&gt;
The first sales were at Jacob's Pharmacy in Atlanta, [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], on May 8, 1886.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/heritage/chronicle_birth_refreshing_idea.html |title= The Chronicle Of Coca-Cola |accessdate=2007-11-28 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt; It was initially sold as a patent medicine for five [[Cent (currency)|cents]]&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2165787/ |title=The Mystery of the 5-Cent Coca-Cola: Why it's so hard for companies to raise prices |first=Tim |last=Harford |publisher=Slate |date=2007-05-11}}&lt;/ref&gt; a glass at [[soda fountain]]s, which were popular in the United States at the time due to the belief that [[carbonated water]] was good for the health.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://memory.loc.gov/ammem/ccmphtml/colatime1.html |title=Themes for Coca-Cola Advertising (1886–1999) |accessdate=2007-02-11 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt; Pemberton claimed Coca-Cola cured many diseases, including [[morphine]] addiction, [[dyspepsia]], [[neurasthenia]], [[headache]], and [[impotence]]. Pemberton ran the first advertisement for the beverage on May 29 of the same year in the ''[[Atlanta Journal]]''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Mark Pendergrast | title=For God, Country and Coca-Cola | publisher=Basic Books | year=2000 | page=32 | isbn=0-465-05468-4 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

By 1888, three versions of Coca-Cola — sold by three separate businesses — were on the market. [[Asa Griggs Candler]] acquired a stake in Pemberton's company in 1887 and incorporated it as the [[Coca Cola Corporation|Coca Cola Company]] in 1888.&lt;ref name=&quot;Pendergrast2000&quot;&gt;Mark Pendergrast (2000). ''For God, Country and Coca-Cola''. [[Basic Books]]. ISBN 0-465-05468-4.&lt;/ref&gt; The same year, while suffering from an ongoing addiction to [[morphine]],&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.faqs.org/nutrition/Biographies/Pemberton-John-S.html |title=Pemberton Bio|accessdate=2009-12-07|work= }}&lt;/ref&gt; Pemberton sold the rights a second time to four more businessmen: [[J.C. Mayfield]], A.O. Murphey, C.O. Mullahy and E.H. Bloodworth. Meanwhile, Pemberton's alcoholic&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | author=Mark Pendergrast | title=For God, Country and Coca-Cola | publisher=Basic Books | year=2000 | page=48 | isbn=0-465-05468-4 }}&lt;/ref&gt; son [[Charley Pemberton]] began selling his own version of the product.&lt;ref name=&quot;Pendergrast&quot;&gt;{{cite book | author=Mark Pendergrast | title=For God, Country and Coca-Cola | publisher=Basic Books | year=2000 | pages=41&amp;nbsp;–45 | isbn=0-465-05468-4 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

John Pemberton declared that the ''name'' &quot;Coca-Cola&quot; belonged to Charley, but the other two manufacturers could continue to use the ''formula''. So, in the summer of 1888, Candler sold his beverage under the names Yum Yum and Koke. After both failed to catch on, Candler set out to establish a legal claim to Coca-Cola in late 1888, in order to force his two competitors out of the business. Candler purchased [[exclusive right]]s to the formula from John Pemberton, Margaret Dozier and Woolfolk Walker. However, in 1914, Dozier came forward to claim her signature on the bill of sale had been forged, and subsequent analysis has indicated John Pemberton's signature was most likely a forgery as well.&lt;ref name=&quot;Pendergrast1&quot;&gt;{{cite book | author=Mark Pendergrast | title=For God, Country and Coca-Cola | publisher=Basic Books | year=2000 | pages=45&amp;nbsp;–47 | isbn=0-465-05468-4 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 1892 Candler incorporated a second company, [[The Coca-Cola Company|''The'' Coca-Cola Company]] (the current corporation), and in 1910 Candler had the earliest records of the company burned, further obscuring its legal origins. By the time of its 50th anniversary, the drink had reached the status of a national icon in the USA. In 1935, it was certified [[kosher]] by Rabbi [[Tobias Geffen]], after the company made minor changes in the sourcing of some ingredients.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.ajhs.org/scholarship/chapters/chapter.cfm?documentID=270 | title=Beyond Seltzer Water: The Kashering of Coca-Cola | publisher = American Jewish Historical Society |accessdate=2007-02-26}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Coca-Cola was sold in [[bottle]]s for the first time on March 12, 1894. The first outdoor wall advertisement was painted in the same year as well in [[Cartersville, Georgia]].&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WM2DK6 First painted wall sign to advertise Coca-Cola : Cartersville, GA] – Waymarking&lt;/ref&gt; [[aluminum can|Cans]] of Coke first appeared in 1955.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://home.comcast.net/~collectiblesodacans/Cokepg1.htm |title=Coke Can History |accessdate=2007-01-21 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt; The first bottling of Coca-Cola occurred in [[Vicksburg, Mississippi|Vicksburg]], [[Mississippi]], at the Biedenharn Candy Company in 1891. Its proprietor was Joseph A. Biedenharn. The original bottles were Biedenharn bottles, very different from the much later hobble-skirt design that is now so familiar. Asa Candler was tentative about bottling the drink, but two entrepreneurs from [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], Benjamin F. Thomas and Joseph B. Whitehead, proposed the idea and were so persuasive that Candler signed a contract giving them control of the procedure for only one dollar. Candler never collected his dollar, but in 1899 Chattanooga became the site of the first Coca-Cola bottling company.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.chattanoogacocacola.com/history.asp |title= Chattanooga Coca-Cola History |accessdate=2008-08-24 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt; The loosely termed contract proved to be problematic for the company for decades to come. Legal matters were not helped by the decision of the bottlers to subcontract to other companies, effectively becoming parent bottlers.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/ourcompany/historybottling.html |title= History Of Bottling |accessdate=2007-02-23 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt;

Coke concentrate, or Coke syrup, was and is sold separately at pharmacies in small quantities, as an over-the-counter remedy for nausea or mildly upset stomach.

===New Coke===
{{Main|New Coke}}
&lt;!--[[Image:Coca-Cola advertisement in Colorado City, TX IMG 4538.JPG|thumb|Coca-Cola sign in [[Colorado City, Texas|Colorado City]], [[Texas]]]]--&gt;
[[Image:newcoke.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Advertising promoting flavor change]]

On April 23, 1985, Coca-Cola, amid much publicity, attempted to change the [[Coca-Cola formula|formula]] of the drink with &quot;New Coke&quot;. Follow-up taste tests revealed that most consumers preferred the taste of New Coke to both Coke and Pepsi, but Coca-Cola management was unprepared for the public's [[nostalgia]] for the old drink, leading to a [[Backlash (sociology)|backlash]]. The company gave in to protests and returned to a variation of the [[Coca-Cola formula|old formula]], under the name Coca-Cola Classic on July 10, 1985.

===21st century===
On February 7, 2005, the Coca-Cola Company announced that in the second quarter of 2005 they planned to launch a [[Diet Coke]] product sweetened with the [[Sugar substitute|artificial sweetener]] [[sucralose]], the same sweetener currently used in [[Pepsi One]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www2.coca-cola.com/presscenter/newproducts_dietcoke_splenda.html |title=Diet Coke Sweetened with Splenda |accessdate=2007-01-06 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.pepsi.com/help/faqs/faq.php?category=pepsi_brands&amp;page=pepsi_one |title=Pepsi Brands&amp;nbsp; — Pepsi One |accessdate=2007-01-06 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt; On March 21, 2005, it announced another diet product, [[Coca-Cola Zero]], sweetened partly with a blend of [[aspartame]] and [[acesulfame potassium]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/7257920/ |title=Coke to launch new no-calorie soda |accessdate=2007-11-28 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt; In 2007, Coca-Cola began to sell a new &quot;healthy soda&quot;: Diet Coke with vitamins B&lt;sub&gt;6&lt;/sub&gt;, B&lt;sub&gt;12&lt;/sub&gt;, magnesium, niacin, and zinc, marketed as &quot;Diet Coke Plus.&quot;

On July 5, 2005, it was revealed that Coca-Cola would resume operations in [[Iraq]] for the first time since the [[Arab League]] boycotted the company in 1968.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|author=Rory Carroll in Baghdad |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2005/jul/05/iraq.rorycarroll |title=Cola wars as Coke moves on Baghdad – The |publisher=Guardian |date= 2005-07-05|accessdate=2011-03-13 |location=London}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In April 2007, in Canada, the name &quot;Coca-Cola Classic&quot; was changed back to &quot;Coca-Cola.&quot; The word &quot;Classic&quot; was truncated because &quot;New Coke&quot; was no longer in production, eliminating the need to differentiate between the two.&lt;ref&gt;According to a Coca-Cola customer-service representative.&lt;/ref&gt; The formula remained unchanged.

In January 2009, Coca-Cola stopped printing the word &quot;Classic&quot; on the labels of {{convert|16|USfloz|ml|adj=on}} bottles sold in parts of the [[southeastern United States]].&lt;ref name=wsj&gt;{{cite news |title=Coke to Omit 'Classic' |first=Betsy |last=McKay |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=January 30, 2009 |url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB123332768434033495.html }}&lt;/ref&gt; The change is part of a larger strategy to rejuvenate the product's image.&lt;ref name=wsj/&gt;

In November 2009, due to a dispute over wholesale prices of Coca-Cola products, [[Costco]] stopped restocking its shelves with Coke and Diet Coke.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |author=Fredrix, Emily and Sarah Skidmore |title=Costco nixes Coke products over pricing dispute |url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hC_n50ZLyl8FLDBIkGfCn7-110BwD9C1F1C80 |agency=Associated Press |date=November 17, 2009 }}{{dead link|date=July 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Use of stimulants in formula==
When launched Coca-Cola's two key ingredients were [[cocaine]] (benzoylmethyl ecgonine) and [[caffeine]]. The cocaine was derived from the [[coca]] leaf and the caffeine from [[kola nut]], leading to the name Coca-Cola (the &quot;K&quot; in Kola was replaced with a &quot;C&quot; for marketing purposes).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.pponline.co.uk/encyc/0204.htm |title=Coca-cola |publisher=Pponline.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-03-13}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;&quot;autogenerated1&quot;&gt;{{cite web |url=http://inventors.about.com/od/cstartinventions/a/coca_cola.htm |title=The History of Coca Cola |accessdate=2007-01-23 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Coca — cocaine===
Pemberton called for five [[ounce]]s of coca leaf per gallon of syrup, a significant dose; in 1891, Candler claimed his formula (altered extensively from Pemberton's original) contained only a tenth of this amount. Coca-Cola did once contain an estimated nine [[milligram]]s of cocaine per glass, but in 1903 it was removed.&lt;ref&gt;Liebowitz, Michael, R. (1983). ''The Chemistry of Love''. Boston: Little, Brown, &amp; Co.&lt;/ref&gt; Coca-Cola still contains coca flavoring.

After 1904, instead of using fresh leaves, Coca-Cola started using &quot;spent&quot; leaves — the leftovers of the cocaine-extraction process with cocaine trace levels left over at a molecular level.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.straightdope.com/classics/a2_033.html|title=Is it true Coca Cola once contained cocaine? |work= |accessdate=2007-02-27}}&lt;/ref&gt; To this day, Coca-Cola uses as an ingredient a cocaine-free [[coca]] leaf extract prepared at a [[Stepan Company]] plant in [[Maywood, New Jersey]].

In the United States, [[Stepan Company]] is the only manufacturing plant authorized by the Federal Government to import and process the [[coca]] plant,&lt;ref&gt;May, Clifford D. [http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DE6D7123BF932A35754C0A96E948260 &quot;How Coca-Cola Obtains Its Coca&quot;], ''[[The New York Times]]'', July 1, 1998. Accessed December 4, 2007&lt;/ref&gt; which it obtains mainly from [[Peru]] and, to a lesser extent, [[Bolivia]]. Besides producing the coca flavoring agent for Coca-Cola, [[Stepan Company]] extracts cocaine from the coca leaves, which it sells to [[Mallinckrodt]], a [[St. Louis, Missouri]] [[pharmaceutical]] manufacturer that is the only company in the United States licensed to purify cocaine for medicinal use.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |first=Drew |last=Benson |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Coca kick in drinks spurs export fears|url=http://www.mindfully.org/Food/2004/Kdrink-Coca-Drink19apr04.htm |quote=}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Kola nuts — caffeine===
[[Kola nut]]s act as a flavoring and the source of [[caffeine]] in Coca-Cola. In Britain, for example, the ingredient label states &quot;Flavourings (Including Caffeine).&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.coca-cola.co.uk/yourhealth/what_our_labels_tell_you/ |title=Coca-Cola Your Health – You and Your Family's GDA Questions Answered |publisher=Coca-cola.co.uk |date=2010-04-13 |accessdate=2011-03-13}}&lt;/ref&gt; Kola nuts contain about 2 percent to 3.5 percent caffeine, are of bitter flavor and are commonly used in [[cola]] [[soft drinks]]. In 1911, the U.S. government initiated [[United States v. Forty Barrels and Twenty Kegs of Coca-Cola]], hoping to force Coca-Cola to remove caffeine from its formula. The case was decided in favor of Coca-Cola. Subsequently, in 1912 the U.S. Pure Food and Drug Act was amended, adding [[caffeine]] to the list of &quot;habit-forming&quot; and &quot;deleterious&quot; substances which must be listed on a product's label.

Coca-Cola contains 46&amp;nbsp;mg of [[caffeine]] per 12 fluid ounces, while [[Caffeine-Free Coca-Cola]] and [[Diet Coke Caffeine-Free]] contain 0&amp;nbsp;mg.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | url=http://books.google.com/?id=WxmBmvhsoZ8C&amp;pg=PA363&amp;lpg=PA363&amp;dq=caffeine+coca+cola | title=Caffeine Content of Some Cola Beverages | work=Google Books | isbn=9780849326479 | author1=Spiller, Gene A | year=1998}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Production==
[[File:Coca-Cola 24 Can Pack.jpg|thumb|Coca-Cola 375 mL cans - 24 pack ([[Australia|AU]])]]

===Ingredients===
* Carbonated water
* Sugar ([[sucrose]] or [[high-fructose corn syrup]] depending on country of origin)
* Caffeine
* Phosphoric acid v. Caramel (E150d)
* Natural flavorings&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.letsgettogether.co.uk/DetailQuestionAnswer/QuestionID=2-color=df0f0b |title=Home of Coca-Cola UK : Diet Coke : Coke Zero – Coca-Cola GB |publisher=Letsgettogether.co.uk |date=2010-04-13 |accessdate=2011-03-13}}&lt;/ref&gt;
A can of Coke (12 fl ounces/355&amp;nbsp;ml) has 39&amp;nbsp;grams of carbohydrates (all from sugar, approximately 10 teaspoons),&lt;ref&gt;1 teaspoon of sugar is ~4 g&lt;/ref&gt; 50&amp;nbsp;mg of sodium, 0&amp;nbsp;grams fat, 0&amp;nbsp;grams potassium, and 140 calories.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailyplate.com/nutrition-calories/food/coca-cola/coca-cola-classic-12oz-can |title=The Daily Plate |publisher=The Daily Plate |date= |accessdate=2011-03-13}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===Formula of natural flavorings===
{{Main|Coca-Cola formula}}

The exact formula of Coca-Cola's natural flavorings (but not its other ingredients which are listed on the side of the bottle or can) is a [[trade secret]]. The original copy of the formula is held in [[SunTrust Bank]]'s main vault in Atlanta. Its predecessor, the [[Trust Company]], was the [[underwriter]] for the Coca-Cola Company's [[initial public offering]] in 1919. A popular myth states that only two executives have access to the formula, with each executive having only half the formula.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/cokelore/ |title=Urban Legends Reference Pages: Cokelore |accessdate=2007-02-10 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt; The truth is that while Coca-Cola does have a rule restricting access to only two executives, each knows the entire formula and others, in addition to the prescribed duo, have known the formulation process.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.snopes.com/cokelore/formula.asp|title=Urban Legends Reference Pages: Cokelore (Have a Cloak and a Smile) |accessdate=2007-02-22 |work= }}&lt;/ref&gt;

On February 11, 2011 [[Ira Glass]] revealed on his [[Public Radio International|PRI]] radio show, ''[[This American Life]]'', that the secret formula to Coca-Cola had been uncovered in a 1979 newspaper. The formula found basically matched the formula found in Pemberton's diary.&lt;ref&gt;Katie Rogers, [http://voices.washingtonpost.com/blog-post/2011/02/this_american_life_bursts_coca.html &quot;'This American Life' bursts Coca-Cola's bubble: What's in that original recipe, anyway?,&quot;] ''[[Washington Post]]'' BlogPost, February 15, 2011, retrieved February 16, 2011.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Brett Michael Dykes, [http://news.yahoo.com/s/yblog_thelookout/20110215/ts_yblog_thelookout/did-nprs-this-american-life-discover-cokes-secret-formula &quot;Did NPR’s ‘This American Life’ discover Coke’s secret formula?,&quot;] The Lookout, [[Yahoo!]] News, February 15, 2011.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;David W. Freeman, [http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-504763_162-20031984-10391704.html &quot;'This American Life' Reveals Coca-Cola's Secret Recipe (Full Ingredient List),&quot;] [[CBS]] News Healthwatch blogs, February 15, 2011.&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/427/original-recipe/recipe The Recipe], ''[[This American Life]]''.&lt;/ref&gt;

===Franchised production model===
The actual production and distribution of Coca-Cola follows a franchising model. The Coca-Cola Company only produces a syrup concentrate, which it sells to bottlers throughout the world, who hold Coca-Cola franchises for one or more geographical areas. The bottlers produce the final drink by mixing the syrup with filtered water and sweeteners, and then carbonate it before putting it in cans and bottles, which the bottlers then sell and distribute to retail stores, vending machines, restaurants and food service distributors.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/ourcompany/aboutbottling.html |title=Coca-Cola&amp;nbsp; — Our Company&amp;nbsp; — About Bottling |accessdate=2007-02-22 |work= |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070216144908/http://www.thecoca-colacompany.com/ourcompany/aboutbottling.html |archivedate = February 16, 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The Coca-Cola Company owns minority shares in some of its largest franchises, like [[Coca-Cola Enterprises]], [[Coca-Cola Amatil]], [[Coca-Cola Hellenic|Coca-Cola Hellenic Bottling Company]] (CCHBC) and [[Coca-Cola FEMSA]], but fully independent bottlers produce almost half of the volume sold in the world.
Independent bottlers are allowed to sweeten the drink according to local tastes.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.cokecce.com/pages/allContent.asp?page_id=84#q1 |title=What Is the Difference Between Coca-Cola Enterprises and the Coca-Cola Company |accessdate=2007-02-22 |work= }}
&lt;/ref&gt;

The bottling plant in [[Skopje]], [[Macedonia (country)|Macedonia]], received the 2009 award for &quot;Best Bottling Company&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://macedoniaonline.eu/content/view/7151/1/ |title=Coca Cola: Macedonia makes the best Coke |publisher=Macedoniaonline.eu |date=2009-06-16 |accessdate=2011-03-13}}&lt;/ref&gt;

