'''Columbia''' ({{IPAc-en|icon|k|ə|ˈ|l|ʌ|m|b|i|ə}}) is the fifth-largest city in [[Missouri]], and the largest city in [[Mid-Missouri]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/GCTTable?_bm=y&amp;-geo_id=04000US29&amp;-_box_head_nbr=GCT-T1-R&amp;-ds_name=PEP_2006_EST&amp;-_lang=en&amp;-format=ST-9S&amp;-_sse=on | title=2006 Population estimates for incorporated July 1, 2006 | work=[[United States Census Bureau]] | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; With a population of 108,500 as of the 2010 Census,&lt;ref&gt;http://2010.census.gov/news/xls/cb11cn49_mo_2010redistr.xls&lt;/ref&gt; it is the principal municipality of the [[Columbia, Missouri Metropolitan Area|Columbia Metropolitan Area]], a region of 164,283 residents.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |title=2007 Metropolitan Area Population Estimates July 1, 2007 |work=[[United States Census Bureau]]
|url=http://www.census.gov/population/www/estimates/metro_general/2007/CBSA-EST2007-07.csv |accessdate=2008-03-26 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080402204232/http://www.census.gov/population/www/estimates/metro_general/2007/CBSA-EST2007-07.csv |archivedate = April 2, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; The city serves as the [[county seat]] of [[Boone County, Missouri|Boone County]] and as the location of the [[University of Missouri]]. The [[college town]] is politically liberal&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2007/11/08/ideological-scales-look-columbias-political-landsc/ | title=Ideological scales: A look at Columbia's political landscape | publisher=[[Columbia Missourian]] | last=Willems | first=Spencer | date=2007-11-08 | accessdate=2008-01-01|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080111151649/http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2007/11/08/ideological-scales-look-columbias-political-landsc/ |archivedate = January 11, 2008|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt; and is known by the nicknames &quot;The Athens of Missouri,&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | last =Switzler | first=William | title=History of Boone County, Missouri | publisher=St. Louis Western Historical Company |year=1882 | pages=220–221}}&lt;/ref&gt; &quot;College Town USA,&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.ccis.edu/day/international/columbia.asp | title=Columbia, Mo -Collegetown U.S.A| work=[[Columbia College (Missouri)|Columbia College]] | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; and &quot;CoMO.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.themaneater.com/stories/2007/10/30/how-como-does-halloween/ | title=How CoMO does Halloween | work=[[The Maneater]] | accessdate=2008-07-18}}&lt;/ref&gt; Over half of Columbians possess a bachelor's degree&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/ACSSAFFFacts?_event=Search&amp;geo_id=&amp;_geoContext=&amp;_street=&amp;_county=Columbia&amp;_cityTown=Columbia&amp;_state=04000US29&amp;_zip=&amp;_lang=en&amp;_sse=on&amp;pctxt=fph&amp;pgsl=010 | title=American Factfinder Columbia, Missouri | work=[[United States Census Bureau]] | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; and over a quarter hold graduate degrees,&lt;ref name = &quot;rkmnym&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/moneymag/bplive/2006/top25s/educated.html | title=Money's best places to live - most educated | work = [[Money Magazine]] | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; making it the 13th most highly educated municipality in the United States.&lt;ref name = &quot;rkmnym&quot;/&gt;

Columbia was settled in [[Pre-Columbian]] times by the [[Mound builder (people)|mound-building]] [[Mississippian culture]] of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]]. In 1818, a group of settlers incorporated under the Smithton Land Company purchased over 2,000&amp;nbsp;acres (8&amp;nbsp;km²) and established the village of Smithton near present-day downtown Columbia. In 1821, the settlers moved and re-named the settlement [[Historical Columbia|Columbia]]—a poetic name for the United States.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | last =Switzler | first=William | title=History of Boone County, Missouri | publisher=St. Louis Western Historical Company |year=1882 | pages=150–166}}&lt;/ref&gt; The founding of the University of Missouri in 1839 established the city as a center of education and research. Two other institutions of higher education, [[Stephens College]] in 1833 and [[Columbia College (Columbia, Missouri)|Columbia College]] in 1851, were also established within the city.

Located among small [[tributary]] [[valleys]] of the [[Missouri River]], Columbia is roughly equidistant from [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]] and [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]]. [[Greater St. Louis]] is {{convert|70|mi|km}} to the East, and the [[Kansas City Metropolitan Area]] is {{convert|100|mi|km}} to the West. Today, Columbia has a highly diversified economy, and is often ranked high for its business atmosphere.&lt;ref name = &quot;bdkfqw&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiaredi.com/pdfs/ColumbiaKudos.pdf |format=PDF| title= Columbia Kudos | work=Columbia Regional Economic Development (REDI) | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; Never a strong center of industry and manufacturing, the city's economic base relies on the education, medical, technology and insurance industries.&lt;ref name = &quot;ckbome&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbia.k12.mo.us/columbia/colhis.htm | title=History of Columbia | work=[[Columbia Public Schools]] | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; Studies consistently rank Columbia as a top city in which to live for educational facilities, health care, technological savvy, economic growth, cultural opportunities and cost of living.&lt;ref name = &quot;bdkfqw&quot;/&gt; The city has been ranked as high as the second-best place to live in the United States by [[Money (magazine)|Money Magazine]]'s annual list, but has not been ranked in the top 100 since 2006.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.relocateamerica.com/missouri/cities/columbia | title=Why you should choose Columbia | work=Relocate America | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; Residents of Columbia are usually described as &quot;Columbians.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.chamber.columbia.mo.us/community/about.asp?Maps | title=Your Community Maps | work=Columbia Chamber of Commerce | accessdate=2008-07-18|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080209060935/http://www.chamber.columbia.mo.us/community/about.asp?Maps |archivedate = February 9, 2008|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== History ==
{{Main|History of Columbia, Missouri}}
&lt;!-- THIS SECTION IS TOO LONG. PLEASE CONSIDER MAKING ADDITIONS TO THE MAIN &quot;HISTORY OF COLUMBIA, MISSOURI&quot; ARTICLE INSTEAD. --&gt; [[Image:CoMoPano1869.jpg|thumb|right|An aerial view of Columbia's downtown district in 1869. The large building on the right is University of Missouri Academic Hall.]]

The Columbia area was once part of the [[Mississippian culture]] and home to the [[Mound builder (people)|Mound Builders]]. When European explorers arrived, the area was populated by the [[Osage Nation|Osage]] and [[Missouri tribe|Missouri]] Indians.&lt;ref name = &quot;syeszw&quot;/&gt; In 1678, [[René-Robert Cavelier, Sieur de La Salle|La Salle]] claimed all of [[Missouri]] for France. The [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] passed by the area on the Missouri River in 1803. In 1806, [[Daniel Boone]] and his sons established a [[salt lick]] {{nowrap|{{convert|40|mi|km|0}}}} northwest of Columbia. [[The Booneslick Trail]] wound from [[Kentucky]] through [[St. Charles, Missouri|St. Charles]] to the lick. In 1818, a group of settlers, incorporated under the Smithton Land Company, purchased over 2,000&amp;nbsp;acres (8&amp;nbsp;km²) and established the village of Smithton less than a mile from current day downtown Columbia.&lt;ref name = &quot;ckbome&quot;/&gt; In 1821, the settlers moved, because of lack of water, across the Flat Branch to the plateau between the Flat Branch and Hinkson creeks in what is now the downtown district. They re-named the settlement [[Historical Columbia|Columbia]]—a popular historical name for the United States.&lt;ref name = &quot;syeszw&quot;/&gt;

The roots of Columbia's three economic foundations—education, medicine, and insurance—can be traced back to incorporation in 1821.&lt;ref name = &quot;ckbome&quot;/&gt; Original plans for the town set aside land for a state university. Columbia College (distinct from today's), later to become The University of Missouri, was founded in 1839. When the state legislature decided to establish a state university, Columbia raised three times as much money as any other competing city&lt;ref name = &quot;skbsjf&quot;&gt;{{cite book | last =Switzler | first=William | title=History of Boone County, Missouri | publisher=St. Louis Western Historical Company |year=1882 | pages=300–310}}&lt;/ref&gt; and [[James S. Rollins]] donated the land that is today the Francis Quadrangle.&lt;ref name = &quot;skbsjf&quot;/&gt; Soon other educational institutions were founded in Columbia such as Christian Female College, the first college for women west of the Mississippi, which later became the current [[Columbia College (Columbia, Missouri)|Columbia College]]. In 1833, Columbia Baptist Female College opened, which later became [[Stephens College]]. The city benefited from being a stagecoach stop of the [[Santa Fe Trail|Santa Fe]] and [[Oregon Trail|Oregon]] trails, and later from the Missouri-Kansas-Texas Railroad. In 1822 the first hospital was set up by [[William Jewell]]. In 1830, the first newspaper began; in 1832, the first theater in the state was opened; and in 1835, the state's first agricultural fair was held. By 1839, the population (13,000) and wealth of Boone County was exceeded in Missouri only by that of [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis County]], which at that time included the [[St. Louis, Missouri|City of St. Louis]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | last =Switzler | first=William | title=History of Boone County, Missouri | publisher=St. Louis Western Historical Company |year=1882 | pages=325–327}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Image:CoMo1919broadway.jpg|thumb|left|A busy day on Broadway in 1919.]]
Columbia's infrastructure was wholly untouched by the [[American Civil War|Civil War]]. Missouri, as a slave state, had Southern sympathies, but remained in the union. The majority of the city was pro-union,&lt;ref name = &quot;ckbome&quot;/&gt; however, the surrounding agricultural areas of Boone County and the rest of central Missouri were decidedly pro-slavery. Because of this, the University of Missouri became a base from which union troops operated. No battles were fought within the city because the presence of union troop dissuaded the confederate guerrillas from attacking, though several major battles occurred nearby at [[Boonville, Missouri|Boonville]] and [[Centralia, Missouri|Centralia]].

In 1963, Columbia become home to the headquarters of both the [[University of Missouri System]], which today serves over 71,000 students,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.umsystem.edu/ums/about/history/| title=History of the University | work=[[University of Missouri System]] | accessdate=2008-07-18}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the [[Columbia College (Columbia, Missouri)|Columbia College system]], which today serves about 25,000 students.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web| url=http://www.ccis.edu/about/ | title=Welcome to Columbia College | work=[[Columbia College (Columbia, Missouri)|Columbia College]] | accessdate=2008-07-18}}&lt;/ref&gt; The insurance industry also became important to the local economy as several companies established headquarters in Columbia, including [[Shelter Insurance]], [[Missouri Employers Mutual]], and [[Columbia Insurance Group]]. [[State Farm Insurance]] has a regional office in Columbia. In addition, the now defunct Silvey Insurance was once a large local employer. Columbia became a transportation crossroads when [[U.S. Route 63 (Missouri)|U.S. Route 63]] and [[U.S. Route 40 (Missouri)|U.S. Route 40]] (which became present-day [[Interstate 70 (Missouri)|Interstate 70]]) were routed through the city. Soon after the city opened the [[Columbia Regional Airport]]. The latter 20th century saw tremendous growth, and by the end of the century the population was over 80,000 in the city proper.&lt;ref name = &quot;dpmpnc&quot;/&gt;

In early 2006, Columbia embarked on a plan&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.gocolumbiamo.com/Public_Comm/Visioning/visioning_overview.php | title=Imagine Columbia’s Future Visioning Overview | work=City of Columbia | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; to manage the continued growth as the city nears 100,000 population. The city is today growing especially towards the [[Missouri River]] in southwest Boone County. The downtown district has maintained its status as a cultural center and is undergoing significant development in both residential and commercial sectors.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news | url=http://www.komu.com/satellite/SatelliteRender/KOMU.com/ba8a4513-c0a8-2f11-0063-9bd94c70b769/d8d58321-80ce-0971-017d-b4f88f4ea5f5 | title=Columbia Marks a milestone | publisher=KOMU news | last=Haile-Selassie |first=Fanna | date=2007-12-14 | accessdate=2008-08-08 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080209030215/http://www.komu.com/satellite/SatelliteRender/KOMU.com/ba8a4513-c0a8-2f11-0063-9bd94c70b769/d8d58321-80ce-0971-017d-b4f88f4ea5f5 |archivedate = February 9, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt; The University of Missouri, which has tremendous economic impact on the city, experienced record enrollment in 2006&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://munews.missouri.edu/news-releases/2007/0820-freshmen-enrollment.php | title=MU Freshman Enrollment Surpasses 5,000 | work=University of Missouri News Bureau | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; and is undertaking significant construction. The city experienced a violent crime spike in late 2007, and the city's growth is often cited as a contributing factor.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news | url=http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2007/11/29/columbia-police-plan-more-patrols-combat-crime-spi/ | title=Columbia police plan more patrols to combat recent rise in crime | publisher=[[Columbia Missourian]] | last=Logan |first=Lee | date=2007-11-29 | accessdate=2008-07-07|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080423053550/http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2007/11/29/columbia-police-plan-more-patrols-combat-crime-spi/ |archivedate = April 23, 2008|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt;

