}}&lt;/ref&gt; HKO (sun, 1961−1990) &lt;ref name = HKO&gt;	
{{cite web
| url = http://www.hko.gov.hk/wxinfo/climat/world/eng/n_america/us/columbia_mo_e.htm
| title = Climatological Information for Columbia, Missouri, United States
| publisher = [[Hong Kong Observatory]]
| accessdate = 2011-01-22	
}}&lt;/ref&gt;
|source 2 = Weather.com (extremes) &lt;ref name= TWC&gt;	
{{cite web
| url = http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/monthly/graph/USMO0193
| title = Monthly Averages for Columbia, MO
| accessdate = 2011−01−22
| publisher = The Weather Channel }}&lt;/ref&gt;
|date=February 2011}}&lt;/center&gt;

Columbia has a climate marked by sharp seasonal contrasts in temperature, falling between a [[humid continental]] and [[humid subtropical climate]] ([[Köppen climate classification|Köppen]] ''Dfa/Cfa'', respectively). Monthly daily averages range from {{convert|27.8|°F|1}} in January to {{convert|77.4|°F|1}} in July, and the annual mean is {{convert|54.0|°F|1}}. The temperature exceeds {{convert|90|°F|0}} on an average 36 days per year, and every few years exceeds {{convert|100|°F|0}}, while 5 to 6 nights of below {{convert|0|°F|0}} conditions can be expected.&lt;ref name = NCDC /&gt; Precipitation tends to be greatest and most frequent in spring, when severe weather is also most common. Snow averages {{convert|26|in|cm|0}} per season, and typically falls in light amounts at a time. Extreme temperatures have ranged from {{convert|−26|°F|0}} in February 1899 to {{convert|113|°F}} in July 1954.

== Cityscape ==
[[Image:Tiger hotel.jpg|thumb|right|Downtown Columbia]]
Columbia's most commonly recognizable architectural attributes reside downtown and within the university campuses. Widely used icons of the city are the University of Missouri's [[Jesse Hall]] and the [[neo-gothic]] [[Memorial Union (University of Missouri)|Memorial Union]]. The [[David R. Francis Quadrangle]] is an example of [[Thomas Jefferson|Thomas Jefferson's]] [[Jeffersonian architecture|academic village]] concept. There are four [[historic district (United States)|historic districts]] listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] within the city: [[Downtown Columbia, Missouri|Downtown Columbia]], [[East Campus Neighborhood]], [[Francis Quadrangle]], and [[North Ninth Street Historic District]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/nrlist.htm | title=Recent Listings | work=[[National Park Service]] | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; The downtown skyline is relatively low and is dominated by the 10-story [[Tiger Hotel]], and the 15-story Paquin Tower.
&lt;!-- This image has been removed until this section grows larger in size.  [[Image:University of Missouri - Memorial Union.jpg|thumb|right|The most prominent example of [[neo-gothic architecture]] in Columbia is the [[Memorial Union (University of Missouri)|Memorial Union Tower]]]] --&gt;

Downtown Columbia is an area of approximately one square mile surrounded by the University of Missouri on the south, Columbia College on the north, and Stephens College to the east. The area serves as Columbia's financial and business district and is the topic of a large initiative to draw tourism, which includes plans to capitalize on the area's historic architecture, and bohemian characteristics.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.downtown.org/index.html | title=Discover The District | work=The District | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; The city's historic residential core lies in a ring around downtown, extending especially to the west along Broadway, and south into the East Campus neighborhoods. Columbia can be divided into roughly 36 neighborhoods and subdivisions.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.gocolumbiamo.com/Public_Comm/Neighborhood_Associations/documents/NAContactList.pdf |format=PDF| title=Columbia, Missouri Neighborhood Associations | work=City of Columbia| accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; The city's most dense commercial areas are primarily located along [[Interstate 70 (Missouri)|Interstate 70]], [[U.S. Route 63 (Missouri)|U.S. Route 63]], Stadium Blvd, Grindstone Pkwy, and the downtown area.

=== Demographics ===

In 2000, the city had a day time population of 106,487.&lt;ref name = &quot;kabzht&quot;/&gt; As of the [[census]]{{GR|2}} of 2000, there were 84,531 people, 33,689 households, and 17,282 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 1,592.8 people per square mile (615.0/km²). There were 35,916 housing units at an average density of 676.8 per square mile (261.3/km²). The racial makeup of the city was 81.54% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 10.85% [[African American (U.S. Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.39% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 4.30% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.04% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.81% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 2.07% from two or more races. 2.05% of the population were [[Hispanics in the United States|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race.{{GR|2}}

There were 33,689 households out of which 26.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 38.2% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 10.3% had a female householder with no husband present, and 48.7% were non-families. 33.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 6.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.26 and the average family size was 2.92.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://columbiamo.areaconnect.com/statistics.htm | title=Columbia population and demographics | work=Area Connect | accessdate=2008-01-11}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In the city the population was spread out with 19.7% under the age of 18,&lt;ref name=&quot;demo&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.citytowninfo.com/places/missouri/columbia | title=Columbia, Missouri | work=City Town Info | accessdate=2008-01-11}}&lt;/ref&gt; 26.7% from 18 to 24, 28.7% from 25 to 44, 16.2% from 45 to 64, and 8.6% who were 65 years of age or older.&lt;ref name=&quot;demo&quot;/&gt; The median age was 27 years.&lt;ref name=&quot;demo&quot;/&gt; For every 100 females, there were 91.8 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 89.1 males.

The median income for a household in the city was $33,729,&lt;ref name=&quot;epo&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.epodunk.com/cgi-bin/incomeOverview.php?locIndex=20205 | title=Columbia, MO | work=Epodunk | accessdate=2008-01-11}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the median income for a family was $52,288.&lt;ref name=&quot;demo&quot;/&gt; Males had a median income of $34,710 versus $26,694 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $19,507.&lt;ref name=&quot;epo&quot;/&gt; About 9.4% of families and 19.2% of the population were below the [[poverty line]],&lt;ref name=&quot;demo&quot;/&gt; including 14.8% of those under age 18 and 5.2% of those age 65 or over. However, traditional measures of income and poverty can be misleading when applied to cities with high student populations, such as Columbia.

== Economy ==
The economy of Columbia is historically dominated by education, healthcare, and the insurance industry.&lt;ref name = &quot;ckbome&quot;/&gt; Jobs in government are also common, either in Columbia or a half-hour away in [[Jefferson City, Missouri|Jefferson City]].&lt;ref name = &quot;vffbdr&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiaredi.com/area_data/LargestEmployers.php | title=Largest Employers | work=Columbia REDI | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Commutes into the city are also common and in 2000 the city had a day time population of 106,487.&lt;ref name = &quot;kabzht&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.missourieconomy.org/pdfs/daytime_population.pdf |format=PDF| title=Daytime Population | work=Missouri Economic Research Center | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[Columbia Regional Airport]] and the Missouri River [[Rocheport, Missouri|Port of Rocheport]] connect the region with trade and transportation. The University of Missouri is by far the city's largest employer.&lt;ref name = &quot;vffbdr&quot;/&gt;

The economy of the metro area is slightly larger than that of the [[Bahamas]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.missourieconomy.org/newsletter/gmp.htm | title=Economies of Missouri Metros Larger than Many Countries | work=Missouri Economic Research and Development | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; With a Gross Metropolitan Product of $5.84 billion in 2004, Columbia's economy makes up 2.9% of the Gross State Product of Missouri.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://usmayors.org/metroeconomies/Top100_2006.pdf |format=PDF| title=The Role of Metro Areas in the U.S. Economy | work=U.S. Conference of Mayors |page=119 |date=March 2006 |accessdate=2009-12-26}}&lt;/ref&gt; Insurance corporations headquartered in Columbia include [[Shelter Insurance]], and [[Columbia Insurance Group]]. Other organizations include [[MFA Incorporated]], [[Missouri State High School Activities Association]] and [[MFA Oil]]. Companies such as [[Socket (Telecommunications Provider)]], [[Datastorm Technologies, Inc.]], [[Slackers CDs and Games]] and [[Carfax (company)|Carfax]]&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.consumeraffairs.com/news04/2006/10/carfax_history.html | title= Carfax History | publisher=Consumer affairs | last=McCormick | first=Lisa Wade | date=2006-10-10 | accessdate=2008-01-04}}&lt;/ref&gt; were founded in Columbia.

MBS Textbook Exchange, regarded as the industry leader in new and used textbooks in the nation was founded in Columbia. It holds the largest inventory of new and used textbooks in the nation. It is also the largest private employer in Columbia.

== Culture ==
[[Image:The blue note.jpg|thumb|right|[[The Blue Note (Missouri)|The Blue Note]], a rock and pop venue downtown.]]
The [[Missouri Theatre Center for the Arts]] and [[Jesse Hall|Jesse Auditorium]] are Columbia's largest fine arts venues. The [[Ragtag Cinema]] host the well-known [[True/False Film Festival]] annually. In 2008, filmmaker Todd Sklar completed [[Box Elder (Film)|Box Elder]], which was filmed entirely in and around Columbia and the [[University of Missouri]]. The University of Missouri's [[Museum of Art and Archaeology]] displays 14,000 works of art and archaeological objects in five galleries for no charge to the public.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://maa.missouri.edu/collections.html | title=Collections | work=Museum of Art and Archaeology | accessdate=2008-01-11|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070819184833/http://maa.missouri.edu/collections.html |archivedate = August 19, 2007|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt; Libraries include the [[Columbia Public Library]], the University of Missouri Libraries, with over three million volumes in [[Ellis Library]], and the [[State Historical Society of Missouri]]. The &quot;We Always Swing&quot; Jazz Series&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://wealwaysswing.org | title=Jazz Series Website | accessdate=2008-05-21}}&lt;/ref&gt; and the [[Roots N Blues N BBQ Festival]]&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://rootsnbluesnbbq.com/ | title=Roots 'N Blues 'N Barbeque Festival Website | accessdate=2008-05-21}}&lt;/ref&gt; bring some of the country's finest Jazz and Blues to Columbia and Central Missouri.

Columbia has a flourishing and progressive music scene thanks in large part to many acts that come out of the University.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.playbackstl.com/content/view/3071/157/ | title=Columbia Music Scene Struggles for Breakthrough | publisher=PLAYBACK:stl | last=McMahoh | first=Bob | date=2006-06-27 | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[Independent music|indie band]] [[White Rabbits (band)|White Rabbits]] was formed while the members were students at the University of Missouri before moving to [[Brooklyn, New York|Brooklyn]] to record and gain a higher profile.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://cornellsun.com/node/24199 | title=World Music Inﬂuences Band White Rabbits | publisher=[[The Cornell Daily Sun]] | last=Weiss | first=Rebecca | date=2007-09-07 | accessdate=2008-01-10}}&lt;/ref&gt; Musical artists from Columbia have been compiled by [[Painfully Midwestern Records]] with the ComoMusic Anthology series, and the &quot;Das Kompilation&quot; release. Although the [[Hipster (contemporary subculture)|hip]] genre continues to give Columbia some music recognition, it is their progressive psychedelic-heavy metal music scene that has garnered some attention lately. There are also local punk and hip-hop scenes that are gaining momentum locally. Country music singer-songwriter [[Brett James]] is also a native of Columbia.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p165888|pure_url=yes}} | title=Brett James - Biography | work=[[Allmusic]] | accessdate=2008-01-10}}&lt;/ref&gt; The song &quot;Whiskey Bottle,&quot; by [[Uncle Tupelo]], is rumored to be about the city of Columbia as it makes specific reference to a sign which used be displayed on a Columbia tackle shop sign which read, &quot;Liquor, Guns, and Ammo.&quot; The sign is now displayed at the downtown location of [[Shakespeare's Pizza|Shakespeare's pizzeria]].

=== Sports ===
[[Image:FaurotField.jpg|thumb|right|An aerial view of sold-out [[Faurot Field]]]]
The University of Missouri's sports teams, the [[Missouri Tigers]], play a significant role in the sports culture of Columbia. [[Faurot Field]], capacity 71,004, is host to both home football games and concerts. The [[Hearnes Center]] and [[Mizzou Arena]] are two other large sport and event venues, the latter being the home arena for [[Missouri Tigers basketball|Mizzou's basketball team]]. [[Taylor Stadium]] is host to the University's baseball team and was the regional host for the 2007 [[NCAA]] Baseball Championship.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.pac-10.org/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/060607aaa.html | title=2007 NCAA Division I College Baseball Regional &amp; Super Regional Schedule &amp; Results | publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] | date=2007-06-07 | accessdate=2008-07-19 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070710180029/http://www.pac-10.org/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/060607aaa.html |archivedate = July 10, 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[Columbia College (Columbia, Missouri)|Columbia College]] has several men and women collegiate sports teams as well. In 2007 Columbia hosted the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics]] volleyball national championship which the Lady Cougars participated in.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiacougars.com/naiavolleyball/ | title=NAIA Volleyball National Championship | work=[[Columbia College (Columbia, Missouri)|Columbia College]] | accessdate=2008-01-09}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Columbia also hosts the [[Show-Me State Games]], a non-profit program of the Missouri Governor’s Council on Physical Fitness and Health. They are the largest [[National Congress of State Games|state games]] in the United States.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.smsg.org/news/index.asp?ID=89 | title=Show-Me State Games 2008 | work=Show-Me State Games | accessdate=2008-01-09}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;HAB&quot; &gt;{{cite web | url=http://360columbia.com/HealthAndBeauty/Fitness/Show-MeStateGames.html | title=Show-Me State Games - About Us | work=360Columbia | accessdate=2008-01-09}}&lt;/ref&gt; The games consist of 26,000–28,000 Missouri amateur athletes (35,000 total athletes&lt;ref name=&quot;HAB&quot; /&gt;) of all ages and ability levels who compete in the [[Olympic Games|Olympic-style]] sports festival every year during July and August. It recently made [[ESPN|ESPN's]] list of &quot;101 Things All Sports Fans Must Experience Before They Die&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.missourinet.com/gestalt/go.cfm?objectid=7400445A-FEBD-956E-DB0E57B1705A969D | title=Show Me State Games Makes ESPN.com's List | publisher=Missourinet | last=Pollock | first=Bill | date=2007-06-28 | accessdate=2008-01-09|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080205191444/http://www.missourinet.com/gestalt/go.cfm?objectid=7400445A-FEBD-956E-DB0E57B1705A969D |archivedate = February 5, 2008|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Situated halfway between St. Louis and Kansas City, Columbians will often have allegiances to the professional sports teams housed there such as: the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], [[Kansas City Royals]]. [[St. Louis Rams]], [[Kansas City Chiefs]], and [[St. Louis Blues (ice hockey)|St. Louis Blues]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2009/11/30/chiefs-and-rams-fans-columbia-remain-dedicated-despite-down-years/ |title=Chiefs and rams fans remain dedicated despite down years| publisher=[[Columbia Missourian]] |accessdate=2009-02-12}} {{Dead link|date=June 2010| bot=DASHBot}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The [[Bianchi cup|NRA Bianchi Cup]] is held every year in Columbia. It is among the most lucrative of all the shooting sports championships.

Starting in 2011, the [[Columbia Enforcers]] [[Women's American football|women's football]] team will begin play as a member of the [[Women's Spring Football League]].

=== Media ===
The city has two daily newspapers, the ''[[Columbia Missourian]]'' in the morning and the ''[[Columbia Daily Tribune]]'' in the afternoon. The ''Missourian'' is directed by professional editors and staffed by [[Missouri School of Journalism]] students who do the reporting, design, copy editing, information graphics, photography and multimedia. The Missourian is associated with the Spanish-English bilingual publication ''Adelante!'' and the youth oriented ''Vox'' magazine.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiamissourian.com/p/about/ | title=About the Missourian | publisher=[[Columbia Missourian]] | accessdate=2008-01-11}}&lt;/ref&gt; With a daily circulation of nearly 20,000, the ''Tribune'' is the most widely read newspaper in central Missouri. The University of Missouri has the independent but official student newspaper, ''[[The Maneater]]'', which is printed bi-weekly. The now-defunct [[The Prysms Weekly|Prysms Weekly]] was also published in Columbia. In Fall of 2009, KCOU News officially launched full operations out of [[KCOU|KCOU 88.1FM]] on the MU Campus. The entirely student run news organization airs a daily newscast &quot;The Pulse&quot; weekdays at 5 p.m.

The city has 14 radio stations and four television channels.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.visitcolumbiamo.com/web/welcome/community/media.php | title=Local Media | work=Columbia Convention and Visitors Bureau  | accessdate=2008-01-11}}&lt;/ref&gt;

{{Columbia MO Radio}}
{{Columbia MO TV}}

== Government and politics ==
{{Main|Government of Columbia, Missouri}}

[[Image:CourthouseCoMo.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Boone County Courthouse (Missouri)|Boone County Courthouse]] within the Boone County Government Center]]
The City of Columbia's current government was established by a [[Home rule municipality|home rule charter]] adopted by voters on November 11, 1974, which established a [[Council-manager government]] that invested power in the [[City Council]]. The City Council is made up of seven members - six elected by each of Columbia's six [[ward (politics)|wards]], plus an [[at-large]] council member, the Mayor, who is elected by all city voters. All members of the council, none of whom receive a salary for their work, are elected to staggered three-year terms. The Mayor, in addition to being a voting member of the City Council, is recognized as the head of city government for ceremonial purposes. Chief executive authority is invested in a [[city manager]], who oversees the day-to-day operations of government.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.gocolumbiamo.com/Council/Columbia_Code_of_Ordinances/Chapter_99/01.html | title=Columbia Code of Ordinances | work=City of Columbia | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Columbia is the county seat of Boone County, and the county court and government center are located there. The City is located in the ninth U.S. [[Congressional district]]. The 19th [[Missouri State Senate]] district covers all of Boone County. There are five [[Missouri House of Representatives]] districts (9, 21, 23, 24, 25) in the city. Columbia is home to a plethora of attorneys and serves as a legal hub and testing grounds for many new laws and grassroot efforts. The principle law enforcement agency is the [[Columbia Police Department]], with the [[Columbia Fire Department]] providing fire protection. [[The Public Service Joint Communications Center]] coordinates efforts between the two organizations as well as the [[Boone County Fire Protection District]] which operates [[Urban Search and Rescue Missouri Task Force 1]].

[[Image:CoMoCityHallJPG.JPG|thumb|left|The Daniel Boone Building functions as Columbia's [[City and town halls|city hall]].]]
The population generally supports [[progressivism|progressive]] causes such as the extensive city recycling programs and the decriminalization of the drug cannabis&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2005/11/10/marijuana-law-gets-new-review/ | title=Marijuana law gets new review | publisher=[[Columbia Missourian]] | last=Zagier | first=Alan Scher | date=2005-11-10 | accessdate=2008-01-01|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080112054253/http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2005/11/10/marijuana-law-gets-new-review/ |archivedate = January 12, 2008|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt; both for medical and recreational use at the municipal level (though the scope of latter of the two cannabis ordinances has since been restricted).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2006/02/21/city-council-revises-pot-ordinance/ | title=City Council revises pot ordinance | publisher=[[Columbia Missourian]] | last=Hammes | first=Joanie |date=2006-02-21 | accessdate=2008-01-01|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080112054254/http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2006/02/21/city-council-revises-pot-ordinance/ |archivedate = January 12, 2008|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt; The city is also one of only four in the state to offer medical benefits to same-sex partners of city employees.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2006/12/19/council-oks-benefits-for-domestic-partners/ | title=Council Oks Benefits for Domestic Partners | publisher=[[Columbia Missourian]] | last=Salazar | first=Anne | date=2006-12-19 | accessdate=2008-01-01|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080112054304/http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2006/12/19/council-oks-benefits-for-domestic-partners/ |archivedate = January 12, 2008|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt; The new health plan also extends health benefits to unmarried heterosexual domestic partners of city employees. On October 10, 2006, the City Council approved an ordinance to prohibit smoking in restaurants and bars. The ordinance was passed with protest, and several amendments to the ordinance reflect this.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2006/10/10/smoking-ban-passes/ | title=Smoking Ban Passes | publisher=[[Columbia Missourian]] | date=2006-10-10 | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt;

=== Sister cities ===
In accordance with the Columbia Sister Cities Program, which operates in conjunction with [[Sister Cities International]], an organization that began under President [[Dwight Eisenhower]] in 1956, Columbia has been given five international [[sister cities]] in an attempt to foster cross-cultural understanding:&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.gocolumbiamo.com/Sister_Cities/| title=Columbia's Sister Cities| work=The City of Columbia| accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt;

{{Col-begin}}
{{Col-1-of-3}}
* {{flagicon|Georgia}} [[Kutaisi|K'ut'aisi]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]
* {{flagicon|Japan}} [[Matto, Ishikawa|Mattō]], [[Japan]]
{{Col-2-of-3}}
* {{flagicon|Romania}} [[Sibiu]], [[Romania]]
* {{flagicon|South Korea}} [[Suncheon, South Korea|Suncheon]], [[South Korea]]
{{Col-3-of-3}}
* {{flagicon|China}} [[Laoshan District]], [[Qingdao]], PRC

{{Col-end}}

== Education ==
[[Image:CoMoMuPano.JPG|thumb|left|The University of Missouri campus late 19th century]]
Columbia and much of the surrounding area lies within [[Columbia Public Schools|The Columbia Public School District]]. The district enrolls over 17,000 students&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbia.k12.mo.us/reports/headct07.pdf |format=PDF| title=Columbia Public Schools enrollment | work=[[Columbia Public Schools]] | accessdate=2008-01-07}}&lt;/ref&gt; and has a revenue of nearly $200 million for the 2007–2008 school year.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbia.k12.mo.us/bcs/bcsbus/PDF%20Files/Budgets/Bdgt0708.pdf |format=PDF| title=Columbia School District Budget | work=[[Columbia Public Schools]] | accessdate=2008-01-09}}&lt;/ref&gt; It is above the state average in attendance percentage and in graduation rate.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://dese.mo.gov/planning/profile/arsd010093.html | title=School Accountability Report Card | work=Missouri Department of Elementary and Secondary Education | accessdate=2008-01-09}}&lt;/ref&gt; The city operates three public high schools which cover grades 10–12: [[David H. Hickman High School]], [[Rock Bridge High School]], and [[Frederick Douglass High School (Missouri)|Frederick Douglass High School]]. Rock Bridge High is one of two Missouri high schools to receive a silver medal by [[U.S. News &amp; World Report]], putting it in the top 3% of all high schools in the nation.&lt;ref name=&quot;rank&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiatribune.com/2007/Dec/20071203News005.asp | title=Rock Bridge gains national recognition | work=[[Columbia Daily Tribune]] | last=Heavin | first=Janese | date=2007-12-03 | accessdate=2008-01-09|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071208015917/http://www.columbiatribune.com/2007/Dec/20071203News005.asp |archivedate = December 8, 2007|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt; Hickman High has been on [[Newsweek]] magazine’s list of top 1,300 schools in the country for the past three years, and has more named presidential scholars than any other public high school in the nation.&lt;ref name=&quot;rank&quot; /&gt;  There are also several private high schools including: [[Christian Fellowship School]], [[Columbia Independent School]], [[Heritage Academy (Columbia, Missouri)|Heritage Academy]], Christian Chapel Academy, and the yet to be built [[Father Augustine Tolton Regional Catholic High School]].&lt;ref name=&quot;CDT1&quot;&gt;{{cite web | last = Braden | first = Jonathon| authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Catholic high has a name as donations still sought| work = | publisher = | date = | url = http://www.columbiatribune.com/news/2009/oct/03/catholic-high-has-a-name-as-donations-still-sought/ | format = | doi = | accessdate = 10/03/2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Image:Jesse through quad.jpg|thumb|right|[[Jesse Hall]] on the [[David R. Francis Quadrangle]]]]
The city has three institutions of higher education: the [[University of Missouri]], [[Columbia College (Columbia, Missouri)|Columbia College]], and [[Stephens College]]. The city is the headquarters of the [[University of Missouri System]], which operates campuses in [[University of Missouri–St. Louis|St. Louis]], [[University of Missouri–Kansas City|Kansas City]], and [[Rolla, Missouri|Rolla]].

== Infrastructure ==
=== Transportation ===
[[Columbia Transit]] provides public bus and para-transit service, and is owned and operated by the city. In 2008, 1,414,400 passengers boarded along the system's six fixed routes and nine [[University of Missouri]] shuttle routes, and 27,000 boarded the Para-transit service.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.gocolumbiamo.com/PublicWorks/Transportation/about-transit.php About Columbia Transit and Para-Transit&lt;!-- Bot generated title --&gt;]&lt;/ref&gt; The system is constantly experiencing growth in service and technology. A $3.5 million&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2007/10/17/moving-greyhound-services-wabash-still-major-goal-/ | title=Moving Greyhound services to Wabash still a major goal for City Council | publisher=[[Columbia Missourian]] | last=Latzko | first=Laura | date=2007-10-17 | accessdate=2008-01-09|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080202084514/http://www.columbiamissourian.com/stories/2007/10/17/moving-greyhound-services-wabash-still-major-goal-/ |archivedate = February 2, 2008|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt; project to renovate and expand the Wabash Station, a rail depot built in 1910 and converted into the city's transit center in the mid-1980s, was completed in summer of 2007.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.gocolumbiamo.com/PublicWorks/Transportation/wabash-station.php | title=Historic Wabash Station Renovation | work= Columbia Public Works| accessdate=2008-07-19}}&lt;/ref&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;In 2007, a Transit Master Plan was created to address the future transit needs of the city and county with a comprehensive plan to add infrastructure in three key phases.&lt;ref&gt;http://www.gocolumbiamo.com/PublicWorks/Transportation/documents/transitmasterplan2007.pdf&lt;/ref&gt; The five to 15-year plan intends to add service along the southwest, southeast and northeast sections of Columbia and develop alternative transportation models for Boone County.
&lt;br /&gt;Fares are $1.00 for adults, and $.50 for children 5-11, for students with valid I.D, for handicapped/Medicare recipients, and for senior citizens age 65 and up. Columbia Transit offers ''FASTPass'' electronic fare cards and issues electronic transfers for accuracy and convenience. Para-transit fares are $2.00 for a one-way trip, and the service area includes all of Columbia. &lt;br /&gt;Buses operate Monday through Saturday, from 6:25am to 6:25pm Monday-Wednesday, 6:25am to 10:25pm Thursday and Friday, and from 1:00am to 7:30pm on Saturday. Buses do not operate on Sunday.

The city's former mayor, [[Darwin Hindman]], is largely in favor of a non-motorized transportation system,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.pednet.org/news2006PrizeWinners.html | title=Columbia Partnership and Mayor Darwin Hindman Win National Active Living Awards | publisher=PedNet Coalition | date=2006-05-04accessdate=2008-07-19|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071027031735/http://www.pednet.org/news2006PrizeWinners.html |archivedate = October 27, 2007|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt; and can often be seen riding his bicycle around the city.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.parade.com/news/2009/09/27-a-free-wheeling-city.html | title=A Free Wheeling City | work= Parade Magazine| accessdate=2009-09-29}}&lt;/ref&gt; Columbia is also known for its [[M.K.T. Trail|M.K.T.]] Spur of the [[Katy Trail State Park]], which allows foot and bike traffic across the city, and, conceivably, the state. It consists of a soft gravel surface, excellent for running and biking. Columbia also is preparing to embark on construction of several new bike paths and street bike lanes thanks to a $25 million grant from the federal government.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.pednet.org/newsFederalAward.html | title=$25 Million of Federal Funding for Columbia's Bike/Ped Network | publisher=PedNet Coalition | date=2005-07-28 | accessdate=2008-01-01|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080222064635/http://www.pednet.org/newsFederalAward.html |archivedate = February 22, 2008|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt; The city is also served by [[Delta Air Lines]] at [[Columbia Regional Airport]], the only commercial airport in mid-Missouri.

[[Interstate 70 (Missouri)|I-70]], [[U.S. Route 63 (Missouri)|US 63]], and [[U.S. Route 40 (Missouri)|US 40]] are the main freeways used for travel to and from Columbia. Within the city, there are three state highways: [[Missouri Route 763|Route 763]], [[Missouri Route 163|Route 163]], and [[Missouri Route 740|Route 740]].

Rail service is provided by the city-owned Columbia Terminal (COLT) Railroad, which runs from the north side of Columbia to Centralia and a connection to the Norfolk Southern Railway.

=== Health systems ===
[[Image:Muhospital.JPG|thumb|right|The [[University of Missouri Hospital]], the largest hospital in Columbia]]
Health care is a large sector of Columbia's economy, with nearly one in six people working in a health-care related profession&lt;ref name = &quot;yhxnoz&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.columbiatribune.com/2007/OurTown/071.asp | title=Hospitals offer a vital indicator of fiscal health | publisher=[[Columbia Daily Tribune]] | date=2007-06-17 | accessdate=2008-01-08|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080203202556/http://www.columbiatribune.com/2007/OurTown/071.asp |archivedate = February 3, 2008|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.avapl.org/training/Columbia/columbia.htm | title=The Columbia Area | publisher=Missouri Health Sciences Psychology Consortium | accessdate=2008-01-09|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080220185630/http://www.avapl.org/training/Columbia/columbia.htm |archivedate = February 20, 2008|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt; and a physician density that is about three times the United States average.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.academyhealth.org/2006/612/arahoa.ppt | format=PPT | title=Physician Migration to the United States, Canada, United Kingdom and Australia | publisher=Academy Health | accessdate=2008-01-09}} {{Dead link|date=June 2010| bot=DASHBot}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name = &quot;zqxfvy&quot;&gt;{{cite web | url=http://chamber.columbia.mo.us/community/profile.asp?Medical | title=Community Profile | publisher=Columbia Chamber of Commerce | accessdate=2008-01-09|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080203135323/http://chamber.columbia.mo.us/community/profile.asp?Medical |archivedate = February 3, 2008|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt; Columbia's hospitals and supporting facilities are a large referral center for the state, and medical related trips to Columbia are common.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://chamber.columbia.mo.us/community/healthcare.asp?HealthCare | title=Health Care | publisher=Columbia Chamber of Commerce | accessdate=2008-01-08|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080209060946/http://chamber.columbia.mo.us/community/healthcare.asp?HealthCare |archivedate = February 9, 2008|deadurl=yes}}&lt;/ref&gt; There are three hospital systems within the city and six hospitals&lt;ref name = &quot;yhxnoz&quot;/&gt; with a total of 1,105 beds.&lt;ref name = &quot;zqxfvy&quot;/&gt; [[University of Missouri Health Care]] operates four hospitals: [[Columbia Regional Hospital]], [[University of Missouri Hospital]], [[Ellis Fischel Cancer Center]] and [[University of Missouri Children's Hospital]]. [[Boone Hospital Center]] is administered by [[Barnes-Jewish Hospital|BJC Healthcare]] and operates several clinics and outpatient locations. [[Harry S. Truman Memorial Veterans' Hospital]] is administered by the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs]].

There is also a large amount of medically-related industry in Columbia. The [[University of Missouri School of Medicine]] uses university owned facilities as teaching hospitals. The [[University of Missouri Research Reactor Center]] is the largest research reactor in the U.S.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://www.missourilifesciences.org/location.php?id=9 | title=Universities | publisher=The Missouri Life Sciences Project | accessdate=2008-01-08 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070808033347/http://www.missourilifesciences.org/location.php?id=9 |archivedate = August 8, 2007}}&lt;/ref&gt; and produces [[radioisotopes]] used in nuclear medicine. The center serves as the sole supplier of the active ingredients in two [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration]]-approved [[radiopharmaceuticals]] and produces [[Fluorine-18]] used in [[PET imaging]] with its [[cyclotron]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url=http://research.missouri.edu/news/stories/061124_murr.htm | title=MU Research Reactor Submits 20-year License Renewal Application | publisher=MU News Bureau | date=2006-11-24 | accessdate=2008-01-01}}&lt;/ref&gt;

